  urldate = {2023-09-07},
  abstract = {Early in this millennium, as scientific journals moved online, their pages began to fill with studies comparing reading with nonreading, print-reading with screen-reading, book-reading with magazine-reading, fiction-reading with non-fiction-reading, literature-reading with the reading of whatever literature is defined against, and even---drilling yet further down---the reading of critically acclaimed fiction with the reading of popular fiction. Some studies measured effects on health; others on wealth; yet others on theory of mind. Policymakers have seized on their findings, ``prescribing'' self-help books; sponsoring lists of novels, memoirs, and poems for people with anxiety and depression; enlisting reading aloud to combat isolation; and advocating discussing, or simply exchanging, books to combat isolation. All these programs share one thing. Their rhetoric pairs advocacy of reading with distrust of the literary critics who practice it for a living. This chapter asks whether the professionals who use the objects of literary criticism to further human flourishing can make use of debates among its methods. Reciprocally, what can those debates take from competing accounts of the worldly work done by literature, or print, or books, or reading?},
